<area  shape="rect" coords="168,30,257,51" href="../explorations/"></area>
<area  shape="rect" coords="168,8,257,28" href="../currentissue.html"></area>
</map>
<A HREF="/cgi-bin/imagemap/chipheaderweb"><IMG ISMAP SRC="../graphics/chipheader.gif" WIDTH="476" HEIGHT="58" usemap="#header" BORDER=0></A><BR><IMG SRC="../graphics/hangerscienceandcit.gif" WIDTH="476" HEIGHT="27"><P>
<TABLE BORDER=0 VALIGN=TOP>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN=TOP WIDTH=160>
<IMG SRC="../graphics/vertwhiteline.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT><BR>
</TD>
<TD VALIGN=TOP WIDTH=360>
<BR>IMAGING<BR><BR>
<CENTER><H2>Engendering Faces</H2></CENTER>
The difference between male and female faces can largely be
captured by a single variable, state Alice J. O'Toole of the
University of Texas at Dallas and Thomas Vetter of the Max
Planck Institute for Biological Cybernetics in Tubingen,
Germany. They analyzed heads of 65 men and 65 women, finding
an average head and a set of corrections to it, called
eigenheads [see SCIENTIFIC AMERICAN, December 1995]. The first
eigenhead, when added to the average head, yielded a male
face; when subtracted, a female face. Subtle variations were
coded for by a different eigenhead.<P>
</font size>
<P><B>by <I>Madhusree Mukerjee</I></B><P>
<P>
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<HR SIZE=4></BODY>
