SRC="../graphics/hangerexplorations.gif"><BR>

<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>MOLTEN CARBONATE FUEL CELLS</H2>

<P><CENTER><IMG SRC="IMG/122396explorationsbox2.gif" WIDTH="346" HEIGHT="174"
BORDER="1">

<BR CLEAR=ALL><FONT SIZE="2"><B>Santa Clara Demonstration.</B> 
Energy Research Corporation of Danbury, Conn., built this two-megawatt
pilot molten carbonate plant for the municipality of Santa Clara, Calif. It is the highest-powered fuel cell
unit in the U.S.</FONT><P></CENTER>

Molten-carbonate fuel cells
are a type of direct fuel cell that eliminate external fuel processors.
Methane (the main ingredient of natural gas) and steam are converted
into a hydrogen-rich gas in the reforming anode or in a reforming
chamber, which are part of the fuel cell stack. The fuel cell
stack comprises two porous electrodes in contact with a molten
salt of lithium-potassium carbonate (LiKCO<sub>3</sub>). It operates at
approximately
650&#176;C. <P>

At the cathode, oxygen (O<sub>2</sub>) and carbon dioxide (CO<sub>2</sub>) are
converted
into carbonate ions. The electrolyte allows carbonate ions to
migrate to the anode. At the anode, hydrogen reacts with carbonate
ions to form water and CO<sub>2</sub>, and two electrons are released. Connecting
the two electrodes through an external circuit completes the flow
of electrons to generate DC electricity. Molten-carbonate fuel cell plants can achieve an electric efficiency
of 50 percent, which is considerably higher than that of a phosphoric-acid fuel
cell plant. <P>


Source: <A
HREF="http://www.nrel.gov/business/international/info-energy/supplies/fossil/fuel-cell.html">National Renewable Energy Laboratory</A>, <A HREF="http://www.metc.doe.gov">DOE Morgantown Energy Technology Center</A>, <A HREF="http://www.ercc.com">Energy Research Corp.</A>


<HR SIZE=4>

</BODY>
</HTML>
