<CENTER>
<H2>ALLAN HILLS METEORITE</H2>
<IMG SRC="IMG/081996explorationsbox1.gif" WIDTH="359" HEIGHT="221" BORDER="0"><P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
Meteorite: ALH 84001<BR>
Location: Allan Hills, Far Western Icefield, Antartica<BR>
Found: 1984<P></CENTER>
This is the meteorite causing all of the excitement about life
possibly existing on Mars. This was the first meteorite found by
the Antarctic team in 1984. The meteorite was initially
identified as a diogenite, a rare type of achrondite meteorite.
It wasn't until October 1993 that David Mittlefehldt caught the
error, and properly identified as as an SNC. (Source: <A HREF="http://www.jpl.nasa.gov/snc/">Jet
Propulsion Laboratory/NASA</A>)
</BLOCKQUOTE>
