<A HREF="/cgi-bin/imagemap/chipheaderweb" TARGET="_TOP"><IMG ISMAP SRC="../graphics/chipheader.gif" usemap="#header" BORDER=0 WIDTH="476" HEIGHT="58"></A><BR><IMG SRC="../graphics/hangerexplorations.gif" WIDTH="476" HEIGHT="27"><P>
<CENTER><H2>BRAIN DAMAGE FROM SPONGIFORM ENCEPHALOPATHY</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="IMG/081296explorations3.gif" BORDER=0></CENTER><P>
Section of the brain of a sheep with scrapie shows changes seen in all of the spongiform
encephalopathies, including BSE in cattle and CJD in
humans. Large empty spots, called vacuoles, can be seen in two
neurons. They are actually located within the cytoplasm of the cells, pushing the nucleus and the
normal contents of the cytoplasm to the margins of the cells. It is these cavities that make infected
brains seem to resemble a sponge, hence the name "spongiform." Normal brain tissue is quite compact,
with no holes and no spaces between the cells. <BR>
(Source: <A HREF="http://www.vetmed.ucdavis.edu/madcow.htm">UC Davis School of Veterinary Medicine</A>) 
