<TD VALIGN=TOP WIDTH=360>
<CENTER>
<H2>Creating a New Cross-Discipline</H2>
Researchers struggle to<BR>
define commong ground.<P>
</CENTER>
What is this new field called "smart materials"? <A
HREF="http://www.enme.umd.edu/sirkis.html">James S. Sirkis</A>,
head of the <A HREF="http://www.enme.umd.edu/smart.html">Smart
Materials and Structures Research Center</A> at the University
of
Maryland, addressed that nagging question in a keynote speech at
the San Diego conference. A palpable tension hung over the
several hundred engineers and scientists in the room as they too
struggled to define their common ground.<P>
Sirkis began his talk with a challenge, pointing out that few of
the ideas these researchers are pursuing are new. "All of these
things we're working on (he cited electrorheological fluids,
fiber optic sensors, and shape-memory alloys as examples) were
in existence even before we were born. The bane of smart
structures is that we tend to rediscover things that have been
around for years." Knocking down some of the walls that tend to
isolate academic and government researchers in one discipline
from those in others might save a lot of needless duplication of
effort, he suggested.<P>
Sirkis then proceeded to quibble with the label "smart
materials"
that is commonly applied to the field. "The materials themselves
are not smart," Sirkis said. "They just provide a certain
function by converting energy from one form to another," turning
electricity into movement or vice versa, a chemical bond into a
voltage, and so on. In some cases, the fascination with the idea
of making ordinary things more intelligent has led to waste, he
argued. "We as a community tend to focus on the exotic.
Sometimes
we ought to say, 'why don't we just use a lawnmower engine?' We
should be willing to embrace more pedestrian technologies."<P>
In the end, Sirkis offered his own view of what smart materials
and structures are all about--a view that seemed to generate
broad consensus in the audience. "Smart structures," he argued,
"is a design philosophy"--not a specific research discipline.
One
of the reasons the field gets no respect, he suggested, is that
"we've been trying to prove to our colleagues that we are a
viable field, yet it's really hard to sell design."<P>
Sirkis ticked off several tenets that he thought characterize
the
smart structures philosophy:
<UL TYPE=DISC>
<LI>machines should behave as if they were sentient; 
<LI>structures should adapt automatically to their physical
environment; 
<LI>autonomy should be an integral part of the object's design
and function;
<LI>the structures should perform novel functions or do their
job in non- traditional ways.
</UL>
As examples, he cited such futuristic technologies as
intelligent
RAM chips, DNA-based computers, quantum-dot computing and
biological (protein-based) data storage. To some in the
audience,
the design features Sirkis described sounded rather weak and
redundant, the applications rather speculative. But most of the
researchers seemed relieved to have a clearer sense of their
mission.<P>
--W. Wayt Gibbs in San Francisco
</font size>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
