<TITLE>
Scientific American
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<map name="header">
<AREA SHAPE="rect" COORDS="460,0,476,57" HREF="http://www.sciam.com/index.html#mainmenu">
<AREA SHAPE="rect" COORDS="166,8,258,30" HREF="http://www.sciam.com/currentissue.html">
<AREA SHAPE="rect" COORDS="168,31,257,50" HREF="http://www.sciam.com/explorations/">
<AREA SHAPE="rect" COORDS="259,0,352,18" HREF="http://www.sciam.com/interview/">
<AREA SHAPE="rect" COORDS="260,18,352,38" HREF="http://www.sciam.com/askexpert/">
<AREA SHAPE="rect" COORDS="259,40,352,58" HREF="http://www.sciam.com/bookmarks/">
<AREA SHAPE="rect" COORDS="352,0,442,18" HREF="http://www.sciam.com/marketplace/mrktindex.html">
<AREA SHAPE="rect" COORDS="353,19,444,40" HREF="http://www.sciam.com/forms/editorletterform.html">
<AREA SHAPE="rect" COORDS="353,41,443,58" HREF="http://www.sciam.com/cgi-bin/search.cgi">
</map>
<A HREF="/cgi-bin/imagemap/chipheaderweb" TARGET="_TOP">
<IMG ISMAP SRC="../graphics/chipheader.gif" usemap="#header" BORDER=0 WIDTH="476" HEIGHT="58">
</A>
<BR>
<IMG SRC="../graphics/hangerexplorations.gif" WIDTH="476" HEIGHT="27">
<P>
<TABLE BORDER=0 VALIGN=TOP>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN=TOP WIDTH=140>
</FONT>
<IMG SRC="../graphics/vertwhiteline.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=8 HEIGHT=1520>
<BR>
<P>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>
</TD>
<TD VALIGN=TOP WIDTH=360>
<CENTER>
<H2>
Advanced Liquid Crystal Displays
</H2>
New technology may lead to
<BR>
brighter, cheaper computer screens
</CENTER>
<P>
The failings of conventional flat panel display technology are familiar
to anyone who has used--or priced--laptop computers. Inexpensive models
have screens that are limited to shades of gray or dim, dingy colors.
More advanced versions, which are capable of showing bright,
fast-changing hues, carry dizzying price tags. (IBM's newest ThinkPad
laptop, which reviewers have cited as one of the first to offer a
display comparable to that of a desktop monitor, lists for about
$8,000.) And all liquid crystal screens suffer from a voracious
appetite for power, sucking batteries dry within a few hours. 
<P>Researchers at Kent State University's
<AHREF="http://alcom.kent.edu/"> Liquid Crystal Institute </A>
have recently demonstrated a new kind of inexpensive display that can
produce clearer images using alot less energy than existing designs.
Commercial production of a high-resolution grayscale version has already
begun at Kent Display Systems in Kent, Ohio. The researchers are now
engineering a low-power, high-contrast color device. 
<P> The displays
can do more with less because they affect light in a different way than
do conventional LCDs. A standard liquid crystal panel filters the light
both going in and coming out. Dots, or "pixels," of liquid crystal
inside the panel naturally twist, or polarize, the light so that it can
pass unimpeded through the second filter. When a pixel is turned on,
it untwists, creating a dark spot where light is
completely blocked. Unfortunately, such polarizing filters reduce the
amount of light going in by half. Changing bright pixels into colored
ones requires yet another filter, which absorbs even more of
the incoming light. LCDs are consequently too dim to use as
computer displays unless illuminated by a lamp from behind. And
lamps devour electricity. 
<P>
<A HREF="http://scorpio.kent.edu/ILCS/Members/Chien_L.C._0013.html">
Liang-Chy Chien </A> and his colleagues at Kent State got around this
problem using a so-called cholesteric liquid crystal material. Rather
than twisting light from one orientation to another, this
material naturally breaks incoming light rays into two parts. One ray
isreflected; the other is transmitted. Electrifying the materialturns
it clear. Because cholesteric LCDs reflect light directly without the
need for polarizing filters, they can appear as bright and legible in
ambient light as conventional LCDs do when electrically backlit. 
<P>
Early cholesteric LCDs were limited to single colors, but Chien found
that if he added small amounts of a second material, he could tune the
color to anything from deep red to brilliant blue by shining various
amounts of ultraviolet light on the panel. He and his collaborators
then locked in the desired color by mixing in a bit of polymer that
fixed the liquid-crystal orientation.The engineers are now adapting
ultraviolet masks like those used to etch microscopic patterns onto
computer chips to create millions of red, blue and green pixels on a
high-resolution cholesteric LCD panel. 
<P> At present, cholesteric LCDs
are about 20 percent more expensivethan conventional "passive matrix"
displays, but there are considerable compensations. Pixels in the new
displays stay on once they are turned on. That permanence eliminates
the need to redraw the display several times each second, saving even
more power. As a result, such panels should run more than 10
times longer on a set of batteries than do present displays. 
<P> The
stability of cholesteric LCDs also makes it possible todesign smaller
pixels--one prototype display boasts 200 dots per inch--and it
eliminates the flicker that makes laptop screens wearisome to read. But
the biggest advantage of the new LCDs is that they do not require the
intricate "active matrix" electronics that triple the price of
conventional panels in order to maintain high contrast and resolution.
Several manufacturers, including IBM, Sony and Toshiba, have reportedly
expressed interest in licensing the technology.
<P>--W. Wayt Gibbs in San Francisco
<P><B>FURTHER EXPLORATION:</B>
<P>
<AHREF="http://www.display.org/sid/sid95/lctech.htm#Multicolor Reflective">
"MulticolorReflective Cholesteric Displays,"
</A>
conference paper by L.-C.Chien, U. Muller, M.-F. Nabor, and J. W. Doane.
<P>
</font size>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
