ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=8 HEIGHT=1520><BR>
<P><BR CLEAR=ALL></TD><TD
VALIGN=TOP WIDTH=360><CENTER><H2>Artificial Muscles</H2>Potential uses
range from<BR>medical devices to machines.</CENTER>
<P>Many machines
can automate some of the functions of human muscles, but few can mimic
the form. Recent research into polymer-based artificial muscles may
soon yield devices that move more like biological organisms.
<P><A
HREF="http://www.nmjc.org/center/faculty/shahinpoor.html">Mo Shahinpoor</A>,
anengineering professor at the University of New Mexico, makes his out
of polyacrylonitrile (PAN), a polymer that in a slightly different form
is known by the trade name Orlon, or artificial silk. Researchers
discovered several years ago that PAN, a tough substance with physical
properties midway between gel and plastic, contracts dramatically when
its acidity (pH) ischanged.
<P>In less than 20 milliseconds, PAN fibers
start shrinking. They can decrease in length by 20 percent in
two-tenths of a second, about as fast a human muscle. Depending on the
acidity, PAN fibers can contract to anywhere from one-half to one-
tenth their original length, Shahinpoor reports. Laboratory tests show
that the fibers are strong, too, capable of holding four
kilograms per square centimeter. A human bicep maxes out at just over
half that.
<P>Don't go running out to the fabric store to create
Orlon muscles, however: the fibers must be chemically treated and
specially packaged to work. Shahinpoor wraps fiber bundles in latex
tubes, through which he then pumps the solution that makes them
twitch. Arranging bundles on opposite sides of a skeleton,
Shahinpoor hasbeen able to make it lift and lower its arm. "One of
ourambitions is to make the largest muscle ever," he beams,
"and the smallest as well." His group claims to have produced
working muscles that are just 200 microns in length; some day they
could be used to control the actions of micro machines.
<P>PAN muscles
are limited by their dependence on a chemical trigger. In everyday
applications, it may not be easy to repeatedly alter the environmental
acidity of the muscle. Aversion that runs on electricity instead and
that will not dry out when exposed to air would be more practical.
<P>At the Smart Structures conference,
<AHREF="http://www.nmjc.org/center/interns/mojarrad.html">Mehran Mojarrad</A>,
a graduate student working with Shahinpoor, reported just such
an invention. By coating a commercially available membrane with
platinum, Mojarrad created plastic sheets that curl when electrodes
are charged on either side. So far the researchers have constructed only
demonstration toys from the material: a boat propelled by a waving fin
of polymer and a flapping machine. But more practical uses for a cheap,
noiseless and highly efficient artificial muscle are probably not far
off.
<P>--W. Wayt Gibbs in San Francisco
<P><B>FURTHER
EXPLORATION:</B>
<P><AHREF="http://www-penninfo.upenn.edu:1962/tiserve.mit.edu/9000/24407.html">Light-activated muscles.</A></font
size></BLOCKQUOTE></TD></TR></TABLE></BLOCKQUOTE><HR
SIZE=4></BODY></HTML>
