<HTML><head>
<title>Scientific American</title>
</head><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<map  name="header">
<AREA SHAPE="rect" COORDS="460,0,476,57" HREF="http://www.sciam.com/index.html#mainmenu">
<AREA SHAPE="rect" COORDS="166,8,258,30" HREF="http://www.sciam.com/currentissue.html">
<AREA SHAPE="rect" COORDS="168,31,257,50" HREF="http://www.sciam.com/explorations/">
<AREA SHAPE="rect" COORDS="259,0,352,18" HREF="http://www.sciam.com/interview/">
<AREA SHAPE="rect" COORDS="260,18,352,38" HREF="http://www.sciam.com/askexpert/">
<AREA SHAPE="rect" COORDS="259,40,352,58" HREF="http://www.sciam.com/bookmarks/">
<AREA SHAPE="rect" COORDS="352,0,442,18" HREF="http://www.sciam.com/marketplace/mrktindex.html">
<AREA SHAPE="rect" COORDS="353,19,444,40" HREF="http://www.sciam.com/forms/editorletterform.html">
<AREA SHAPE="rect" COORDS="353,41,443,58" HREF="http://www.sciam.com/cgi-bin/search.cgi">
</map>
<A HREF="/cgi-bin/imagemap/chipheaderweb" TARGET="_TOP"><IMG ISMAP
SRC="../graphics/chipheader.gif" usemap="#header" BORDER=0 WIDTH="476"
HEIGHT="58"></A><BR><IMG SRC="../graphics/hangerexplorations.gif"
WIDTH="476" HEIGHT="27">
<P><TABLE BORDER=0 VALIGN=TOP><TR><TD
VALIGN=TOP WIDTH=140></FONT><IMG SRC="../graphics/vertwhiteline.gif"
ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=8 HEIGHT=1520><BR>
<P><BR CLEAR=ALL></TD><TD
VALIGN=TOP WIDTH=360><CENTER><H2>Embedded Sensors</H2>Spotting
damage<BR>before it is too late.</CENTER>
<P>The sorry state of
America's bridges is an all-too-familiarstory. Most collapses occur on
shorter spans, but many largebridges, their maintenance long
underfunded, also are riddledwith cracks and weak spots. Concrete
bridges are at higher riskthan steel, because their flaws are often
less apparent. So itissomewhat surprising that technology is rarely
used to routinelymonitor the health of concrete bridges. All the more
soconsidering how cheaply and easily it could be done.
<P>In a paper
presented at the Smart Materials and Structures conference, D. D. Chung
of the State University of New York at Buffalo described her team's
experiments with "self- monitoring concrete." Her strategy was
deceptively simple. First, mix a tiny amount of carbon fibers in with
the concrete mix (Chung used just 0.05 percent by volume). Then place
electrodes at each end of the bridge and measure its resistance. As
cracks develop, they separate the fibers (which conduct electricity),
thereby increasing the electrical resistance. Taking just a few
basic measurements, Chung was able to deduce with surprising
accuracy the extent of fractures within a bridge, the
consequent reductionin its strength, and the probability that it had
suffered serious damage.
<P>A group of researchers at
<AHREF="http://www.ino.qc.ca/Externe/Doc/Anglais/Home/INO-NOI-Home.html">Canada'sNational
Optics Institute</A> applied a similar idea, albeit with much more
sophisticated technology, to measure the stress on an icebreaker's
propeller as it chopped through the frozen Arctic Ocean. The job
was especially tricky because the blades spin 160 times a minute and the
prop is huge: it stretches 16 feet in diameter and weighs four tons.
Stress varies wildly from one blade to the next and changes rapidly in
time, so the researchers needed a scheme that could measure strain at
54 points on the propeller and repeat the measurement several times a
second.
<P>Their ingenious solution was to dig gouges into the blades
and run hair-thin optical fibers in the tiny indentations.
Each fiber terminated in a strain sensor at one end and a computer
board (mounted directly onto the rotating prop shaft) at the other.
As the electronics spun with the blades, they radioed strain data back
to a workstation on board. "We were lucky to get the icebreaker into
some extremely heavy ice on our first test--actually so bad that it
almost damaged the propeller,"said Andre Marin of the National Optics
Institute, with a scientist's perverse appreciation of the rare
opportunity to get real-world data.
<P>Had it not been for the sensors,
Marin said, the ship's captain may well have pushed the prop beyond its
breaking point. Good thing the equipment worked on the first
try.
<P>--W. Wayt Gibbs in San Francisco</font
size></BLOCKQUOTE></TD></TR></TABLE></BLOCKQUOTE><HR
SIZE=4></BODY></HTML>
