<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE> RADM Examples </TITLE>
<!-- Created by: Gilbert BARROT, 08-Jan-1996 -->
<!-- Changed by: Gilbert BARROT, 12-Jan-1996 -->
<!-- Changed by: Jean-Michel Augusto, 29-Jan-1996 -->
</HEAD>

<BODY  BACKGROUND="/gifs/fond.jpg">

<HR>

<CENTER>
<H1> 
RADM Examples<P>
A86-A4 freeways<P>
</H1>
</CENTER>

<HR>

<H2> Emissions due to a freeway </H2>

<H3> Freeway emission conditions </H3>
<BIG>
<UL>
<LI> Emission height = 0.0 m
<LI> Equivalent diameter = 21.4 m
<LI> Temperature = 302 K
</UL>

The freeway traffic is simulated thanks to a set of discrete sources located all along the several lanes. In this study, 392 equivalent sources have been used.<P>

At each source, 0.32 g/s of pollutant is injected in the computational domain for the South and North lanes of the A86 freeway and 0.63 g/s is injected for the South and North lanes of the A4 freeway.<P>

The numerical simulations have been performed in a first step by taking into account the pollution induced by the freeway alone (see figures 1 and 3) and in a second step by adding the pollution due to the A4 freeway tunnels. The increase of NO2 concentration due to these tunnels is visible in the figure 2. Several wind speeds and direction and several atmospheric stabilities have been used to estimate their impact upon the NO2 concentration around the exits of the A4 tunnels.<P>

<H3> Atmospheric conditions </H3>
<UL>
<LI> Atmospheric stability type D (neutral)
<LI> Wind : logarithmic profile : 5.0 m/s at 10 m
<LI> Ambiant temperature = 300 K
<LI> Ground roughness = 0.3 m
<LI> Mixing height = 150 m
</UL>

<HR>

<CENTER>

