<title>Human Capital and Mobility (HCM)</title>
</head>

<body BACKGROUND="/gifs/fond.jpg">

<p>
<H1>Human Capital and Mobility (HCM)</H1>
<img src="/gifs/bar_marbre_noir2.gif"><br><br>

Network Contract Ndeg. ERBCHRXCT930312
<BIG>
<br><br>
<u>extended by a</u>
<br><br>
Cooperation in science and technology with central and eastern european countries and with new independent states of the former Soviet Union (PECO)
<hr><br>
<H2>INTEGRATION OF REMOTE SENSING, IN-SITU OBSERVATIONS AND NUMERICAL MODELLING APPLIED TO THE NORTHEAST ATLANTIC</H2>
<br>
<b>PROGRESS MEETING</b>
<br>
<b>Sophia-Antipolis</b>
<br>
<b>28-29 March, 1995</b>
<br>
<b><u>Participants:</u></b>
<br>
<p>
<b>-	Drs. Marcel BABIN, Odile HEMBISE &amp; Philippe BARDEY</b><br>
	M&eacute;canique appliqu&eacute;e et Science de l'environnement - ACRI<br>
	230, Route du Pin Montard<br>
	B. P. 234<br>
	06904 Sophia Antipolis C&eacute;dex<br>
	France<br>

<br>
-	<b>Dr. Gennady A. Kivman</b><br>
	P. P. Shirshov Institute of Oceanology<br>
	199053 St. Petersburg<br>
	Russian Federation<br>
<br>

-	<b>Dr. Vera DJEPA-PETROVA</b><br>
	Space Research Institute<br>
	Bulgarian Academy of Science<br>
	Moskovska 6, Sofia 1000<br>
	Bulgaria<br>
<br>

-	<b>Dr. Roxana BOJARIU</b><br>
	National Institute of Meteorology and Hydrology<br>
	Sos. Bucharesti-Ploiesti 97<br>
	71552<br>
	Romania<br>
<br>

-	<b>Dr. Angelo Rubino</b><br>
	Zentrum f&uuml;r Meeres-und Klimaforschung<br>
	Institute f&uuml;r Meereskunde - Universit&auml;t Hamburg<br>
	Troplowitzstr. 7<br>
	D-2000 Hamburg 54<br>
	Germany<br>
<br>

-	<b>Marguerita Esteban</b><br>
	Programa de Clima Maritimo y Banco de Datos Oceanograficos<br>
	Puertos del Estados<br>
	Avenida del Partenon - 10<br>
	28042 Madrid<br>
	Spain<br>
<br>
<br>
<hr>
<b><u>AGENDA</u></b>
<br><br>
<b><cite>Thuesday March 28, 1995</cite></b>
<br>

<b>09:30	Introduction</b>
<br>
<b>10:30	Presentations by members of their general activities and of their current or expected works in the frame of the network</b>
<br>
<b>12:00	Presentation of the Primary production - mixed layer project</b>
<br>
<b>14:15	LUNCH</b>
<br>
<b>15:45	Discussion on collaborations</b>
<br>
<b>17:15	Arrangements of travel expences</b>
<br>
<b>20:00	DINNER in Villefranche-sur-Mer</b>
<br>

<b><cite>Wednesday March 29, 1995</cite></b>
<br>
<br>

<b>09:00	Presentation of electronic network facilities at LPCM</b>
<br>
<b>10:00	Discussion on data exchanges</b>
<br>
<b>12:00	LUNCH</b>
<br>
<b>13:30	Determination of a Schedule for tasks completion</b>
<br>
<b>16:00	Discussion on admistration of PECO funds</b>
<br>
<b>19h00	End</b>
<br><br><br>
<b><u>Rationale of the meeting</u></b>
<br>
<br>
<u>This progress meeting was an initiative of the network coordinator.  It
aimed at:</u>
<br><br>
<ol>
<li>Introducing the new members of the network (PECO programme);
<br>	
<li>Gathering for the first time all post-doc involved in the network (some of
them joined the network only recntly);
<br>	
<li>Establishing concrete exchanges and delays.
</ol>
<br>
After an oral presentation given by each participants of their activity in the frame of the network, and of expectations from the network, detailed discussions were conducted on the way to partition intra-network contributions. It led to fruitful discussions and concrete agreements.  To set clearly the output of these discussions, each participant wrote a short text describing:
<br>
<ol>
<li>The main activity they will conduct within the network;
<br>	
<li>The contribution they expect from other partners;
<br>	
<li>The contribution they can provide to other network projects.
</ol>
<br>
<b><u>Contributions and data exchanges</u></b>
<br><br>
<b><i>Margarita Esteban</i></b>
<br>
<br>
<b>Region of interest:</b>
<br>
<ul>
<li>Canary Islands near field at 28deg.N
<br>	
<li>Canary Islands far field at 20-35deg.N, 23deg.W (east coast)
</ul>
<b>Main activity:</b>
<br><br>
Simulating island processes such as Lee effects, eddy (formation/structure/dissipation) and upwelling.  The 1'-bathymetry data file from Ecole des Mines will be used.
<br>
<br>
<b>Interest in obtaining useful elements from collabotions within the network:</b>
<br>
<ol>
<li>Satellite images of SST and ocean color showing these island effects and any such other peculiar (interesting) features of this region.  These data are expected from JRC and ACRI.
<br>	
<li>Boundary conditions (flux) as a forcing parameter in the model.These informations are expected from Shirshov Institute of Oceanology.
<br>	
<li><i>In situ</i> measurements from cruises conducted in this region, providing temperature and chlorophyll concentration as a function of depth. Such data are expected from Institut f&uuml;r Ostseeforschung and ACRI.
<br>	
<li>Statistical analyses of digitized satellite images and results from numerical simulations.  These analysis should be performed by the National Institute of Meteorology and Hydrology (Romania).
</ol>
<br>
Collaboration is expected through comparison of numerical simulations with both <i>in situ</i> and satellite data (including detection of features through a statistical approach).
<br><br>

<b>Available to the other partners:</b>
<br><br>
At Clima Maritimo, CD's with data banks such as Iseler &amp; Hasse climatological data and NOAA atmospheric data are available.
<br><br>

<b><i>Dr. Vera DJEPA-PETROVA</i></b>
<br><br>

<b>Main activities:</b>
<br>
<ol>
<li>Physical modelling of propagation of radiation through atmosphere in the spectral intervals of satellite data.
<br>	
<li>Algorithms and software for deriving atmospheric and sea state parameters from satellite data.
<br>	
<li>Satellite data processing and analyses of particular sea state and atmospheric phenomena.
<br>	
<li>Application of remotely sensed measurements for oceanoography, sea state, atmospheric and climate research.
</ol><br>

<b>Contribution to the Network:</b>
<br>
<ol>
<li>Models, algorithms and software development (if they are not available) for deriving sea surface physical parameters (sea surface temperature, etc) by satellite data (AVHRR, etc).
<br>	
<li>Processing and analyses of satellite data in order to estimate and examine sea state phenomena.
<br>	
<li>Models development for atmospheric correction of the remotely sensed data provided by future satellite systems, considering there spectral intervals, viewing angles and resolution.
<br>	
<li>Modelling and data processing in order to examine the most informative spectral intervals for estimation of biological, chemical and physical properties of the sea state, considering the current and future satellite systems.
</ol><br><br>

<b><i>Dr. Angelo Rubino</i></b>
<br><br>

<b>Main activity:</b>
<br><br>
In the frame of the northeastern Atlantic upwelling system, an often observed phenomenon (CTD measurement) provides the bases for the contribution in the project.  In semi-enclosed coastal areas, anomalous T-S characteristics were observed: from the surface to the bottom both salinity and temperature show in fact a considerable increase.  The explanation for such a behaviour is that abrupt, very intense evaporation events homogenize the water column at the coast, leading to the formation of a bottom to surface layer, which is subject to geostrophic adjustment.  It evolves in a bottom arrested current which mixes with the ambient water and tranfers to the bottom the acquired properties.
<br><br>
In order to simulate such a phenomenon, a two layer, nonlinear, hydrostatic shallow water numerical model was developed, which can describe the evolution of localized layers and the outcropping of a deep layer.  To achieve this, a set of movable boundary conditions has been applied, so that the bottom arrested current can find its way on the ocean floor.  The layers allow for material mixing by means of an entrainment parametrization.  The first results show the capability of the model to reproduce geostrophical ajustment
processes.
<br><br>

<b>Possible contributions from the other participants:</b>
<br><br>
The proof of the existence of the quoted phenomenon lies in the measurements conducted by Institut f&uuml;r Ostseeforschung.  In this context, the availability of the <i>in situ</i> data set is a fundamental requisite.  It will provide at first a model verification and validation, and moreover these data could be used by the National Institute of Meteorology and Hydrology (Romania) to detect significant statistical time and space variability.  On the other hand, it is probable that such surface to bottom density anomalies have been detected by remote sensing means, both in SAR and in surface temperature, and in color imagery (in fact, for the last point, the presence of a bottom arrested current should lead to a decrease in the phytoplankton content in the water column).  ACRI and Bulgarian Space Research Institute could carry a inspection of the available remote sensing imageries to detect the phenomenon. A quantification of the forcing playing a role in the phenomenon (wind and heat fluxes) could represent another aspect of the collaboration with the partners which are more involved in data acquisition and analysis.

<br><br>
<b>Contribution to other network projects:</b>
<br><br>
We can provide to the other partners the quoted numerical model.
<br><br>

<b><i>Dr. Roxana BOJARIU</i></b>
<br>
<ol>
<li>The original contribution of our team to the network is the study of the short term climate variability over Atlantic-European region, due to the air-sea interactions.  The predictive potential of the North Atlantic Oscillation (NAO) will be assessed by means of Canonical Correlation Analysis (CCA) and Principal Oscillation Pattern (POP) applied to sea surface temperature, surface winds and outgoing longwave radiation (OLR) data.  The effect of air-sea interaction on European temperature and precipitation
anomalies will be also analyzed.
<br>	
<li>From the other members of the network, I need some remote sensing data for the SST and OLR.  From the team of Shirshov Institute of Oceanology, we hope to get the response of their ocean model to the surface wind anomalies characteristics for the NAO models.  The composites of the sea wind characteristic for the NAO phases will be provided by us.
<br>	
<li>For the project proposed by ACRI, we could use the statistical methods for the validation tasks an for estimating statistically some parameters of the model.  For projects proposed by Clima Maritimo and University of Hamburg, we could make statistical analyses of the <i>in situ</i> and remote sensing observations in order to reveal characteristic patterns of the phenomena described by their models.  We could also statistically analyze the ouput of their models.
</ol>
<br>

<b><i>Dr. Gennady A. KIVMAN</i></b>
<br><br>
<b>Work planned to be done:</b>
<br>
<ol>
<li>Reproducing climatic circulation in the North Atlantic ans seasonal evolution of the upper mixed layer (UML) by means of a quasi-geostrophic circulation model with interactive upper mixed layer.
<br>	
<li>Development of a robust 4-component (phytoplankton-zooplankton-detritus-nitrogen) ecosystem model and coupling it with the circulation model.
<br>	
<li>Developing a data assimilation technique directed to fit the ecosystem model to satellite chlorophyll <i>a</i> concentration data.
</ol>
<br>
<b>What we will be able to distribute:</b>
<br>
<ol>
<li>Depths of the UML for the North Atlantic as a function of time for different geographical regions.  It may be used as an input for other ecosystem models (for example, that presented by ACRI).
<br>	
<li>Volume transport to be used in fine-resolution models for a concrete region (for example, that studied by Clima Maritimo).
<br>	
<li>The data assimilation technique to be developed for utilization in other ecosystem models.
</ol><br>

<b>What we would like to get from other partners of the network:</b>
<br>
<ol>
<li>Satellite data on chlorophyll <i>a</i> concentration.
<br>	
<li>Temporal data on solar radiation measured at some stations (it would be fine
if they are accompanied by temperature and salinity data).
<br>	
<li>Data on surface temperature, cloudiness, wind velocity as well as fields of temperature, salinity and nutrients in the seasonal and main thermoclines to be utilized in our circulation model.
</ol>
<br>
<b><i>Dr. Marcel BABIN</i></b>
<br><br>
<b>Activity conducted in the frame of the network subject to collaborations:</b>
<br><br>
One of the most important component in models describing the flux of carbon from atmosphere to ocean sediments is phytoplankton primary production, i.e. the rate of net  carbon fixation.   Primary production represents the input way of inorganic carbon into the ocean organic carbon pool.  During the last 7 years, efforts have been deployed by oceanographers, in the frame of the Joint Ocean Global Flux Study (JGOFS), to develop primary production models applicable at global  scale using remotely sensed variables, namely sea suface chlorophyll <i>a</i> concentration.  Such a model has been developed by Morel (1991), and validated and applied at global  scale (e.g. Berthon and Morel 1992, Antoine and Morel <i>in press</i>).  Although this model proved to perform well (measured and prediction values agree within a factor of  3 while primary production varies over 4 orders of magnitude), improvements are still needed.
<br><br>
The examination of the different ways allowing significant improvements of this model led us  to identify the depth of the upper mixed layer (Zml) as the most important source of original information to be added to the model.  Combined with the depth of the euphotic zone  (depth at  which irradiance is 1% that  at surface; Ze), it should provide a better parameterization of depth variations in chlorophyll <i>a</i> concentration.  Morevover, predictions of photosynthetic parameters may be for the first time possible.
<br><br>
To be used in the primary production model of Morel (1991), Zml  must be available at a spatial and temporal resolution similar to that of ocean color data.  A technique based on remotely sensed sea surface temperature and wind speed allowing estimation of Zml has recently been proposed by Yan et al. (1991).  Alternatively, Zml could be provided by a large-scale circulation model.
<br>
<br>
<b>Possible contribution from the other partners:</b>
<br>
<ol>
<li>In providing SST and wind speed images (Bulgarian Space Research Institute).
<br>	
<li>In providing a comparison between Zml predictions from Yan's and Shirshov Institute large-scale circulation models.
</ol>
<br>
<b>Contribution to other projects:</b>
<br>
<ol>
<li>In providing ocean color images (CZCS) for the Northeast Atlantic ocean.
<br>	
<li>In providing in situ data for validation of small- and large-scale circulation models.
</ol>
<br>
<b><u>Actions</u></b>
<br>
<br>

<b>Next progress meeting:</b>
<br>
It was agreed to hold the next HCM/PECO progress meeting at Clima Maritimo (Madrid) begining of June.  To facilitate programming of flight schedules, the meeting must be held close a weekend.  Invitations must be quickly sent by Clima Maritimo to PECO partners for visa formalities.  Finally, it was proposed to hold a 2-day meeting.
<br>
<br>

<b>Progress in collaborations:</b>
<br>
<ul>
<li>Concerning PECO partners, the delay before the next meeting should allow them to study more deeply the different projects conducted by the network.  Thereby, they should be in a better position to propose more concrete contributions during the next progress meeting.  This meeting will also allow to gather all network members and, therfore, to organize visits in the different laboratories to facilitate completion of specific tasks (e.g. a possible long stay of Vera DJEPA-PETROVA at JRC to process remote sensing data should be discussed).
<br>	
<li>In order to obtain useful remote sensing and in situ data from the other partners, Dr. Angelo RUBINO will provide to the other partners the exact location and time period over which data should be provided.
<br>	
<li>An inventory of CZCS scenes covering the Northeast Atlantic, already obtainable by ACRI, will be provided by Dr. Marcel BABIN.
</ul>
<br>

<b>Administration of funds:</b>
<br><br>
Thorough discussions took place on how to manage in the most efficient way PECO funds.  From these discussions, it appeared to be a delicate task and that it would be the best to manage funds through ACRI.  To succeed in this way, official documents should be provided by institutions participating in the PECO programme.  These documents should indicate clearly that they allow ACRI to manage these funds.  Also,  the institutions will have to provide every year a status of expences covered by PECO and laid out by ACRI, in local currency.
<br><br>

