<TITLE>RESULTS OVERVIEW</TITLE>

<!-- Changed by: Jean-Michel Augusto, 26-Jan-1996 -->

</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/gifs/fond.jpg">


<p align=center><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="gif/header.gif" ALT="Header">

<P>

<H1>RESULTS OVERVIEW</H1>

<img src="/gifs/bar_marbre_noir2.gif"><br><br>
<P> <H1>Introduction</H1>
<big>

The overall objectives stated in the initial proposal are: <P>

<UL>

<LI>to generate, archive and analyse multiannual time series of remote
sensing, in situ and meteorological data for a basic evaluation of
time scales, variability and trends;

<LI>to develop algorithms that relate variables available from remote
sensing, ocean platforms and other observations to processes occurring
in the water column as for example heat flux, primary productivity and
trace gaz fluxes;

<LI>to select and develop models of the upper layer of the ocean to
assimilate remote sensing and other data for process studies and for
future contributions to global models.

</UL>

<P>

The following is a short description of the progress of the work to
date within each of these objectives, where the network activity is
emphasised.

<P>

<H1>1- Archives and time series analyses</H1>

In order to provide a general access to a common database, ACRI-Sophia
Antipolis proposed a technical solution based on the World-Wide Web
(WWW) concept. A major advantage with the WWW is that it allows to
share data distributed in different computers (at different
locations).  The user can access the different data without knowledge
about location of softwares used to manage the data base.  In the
frame of the current project, three WWW servers were installed; at
ARMINES - Sophia Antipolis, ACRI and Intitut f&uuml;r Meereskunde (IM)
- Hamburg .  These servers are connected to already existing servers
at JRC - Ispra and Clima Maritimo (CM) - Madrid.  To facilitate
exchanges between the different servers, the ACRI server has the
specific role of co-ordination to provide information of general
interest.  <P>

This experimental system can be connected via WWW client at
<A HREF="http://www.acri.fr/">http://www.acri.fr/</A>.

<P> To allow the set up of data archives, the first task undertaken
during 1994 concerned the determination of a common frame for data
file storage, which accounts for the various temporal and spatial
scales typical of the data sources involved in this project,
i. e. various satellite sensors, in situ techniques and computational
products.  This task was essentially undertaken by ARMINES who
proposed a common bathymetry digital map including shorelines.  They
also installed a data server with softwares for satellite data
processing and a GIS package (Geographical Information System),
accessible to other members of the network by electronic links.  The
<A HREF="select_ref.html">bathymetry digital map was created
for the area under study in this network, i.e. between 18 and 26&iexcl;N,
and 8 and 20&iexcl;W</A>.

<P>

Up to now this data frame has been fed (1) by CM who provided the
bathymetry and coastline information, (2) by Institut f&uuml;r
Ostseeforschung (IO) -Warnem&uuml;nde who provided in situ
oceanographic data and (3) by JRC who provided <A
HREF="select_avhrr.html">remotely sensed temperature data</A>
(AVHRR).  Finally, the WWW server operated at CM makes fully available
long term series obtained from wave buoys and tidal gauges deployed in
the vicinity of Canary Islands.

<P>

Consistently with the initial proposal, in 1994, two oceanographic
cruises (R. V. Hudson and Humbolt) were conducted by IO off
Mauritania, during which a large amount of physical, chemical and
biological data were obtained.  These are available for the network.

<P> <H1>2- Algorithm development</H1>

During 1994, algorithm development within the network has followed
essentially two lines.  Firstly, JRC processed
<A HREF="select_czcs.html">satellite data for estimation of
phytoplankton biomass</A>, in order to assess the impact of primary
production on <A HREF="dms.html">DMS</A> production and generation of clouds in the Northwest
African upwelling.  This study was also based on meteorological and in
situ data, as well as on multi-annual time series of satellite
observations to investigate long-term regional and temporal variations
of selected surface parameters.  The resulting DMS model can be used
directly on JRC WWW server.  ARMINES, which is involved in long-term
projects on the detection of clouds in satellite imagery and retrieval
of their characteristics, obtained more accurate and efficient
processing of the Meteosat satellite data using the data provided by
IO (in situ) and JRC (AVHRR).  Maps of shortwave radiation have been
produced and made available to the network in October 1994.  Maps of
longwave radiation are being produced.  They will also be available to
the network.  A study is planned in which a comparison between results
obtained by JRC and ARMINES will be performed.

<P> Secondly, the first results from the "two layer, nonlinear,
hydrostatic shallow water equation model" have been obtained at IM for
an idealistic scenario: on flat bottom and smooth slopes.  The model
seems to reproduce in a quite satisfactory way the geostrophic
adjustment processes.  These results will be validated over the shelf
area of the Northwest African coasts from
<A HREF="select_bathy.html">remote sensing measurements
(JRC) and in situ observations (IO), and using the bathymetry fields
provided by ARMINES</A>.

	
<H1>3- Global models development</H1>

<P>

The third objective of current project concerns the development of
global models.  Its achievement represents the main goal for 1995.
The contributions of the different teams are described below.  <P>

<ADDRESS> Programa de Clima Maritimo y Banco de Datos
Oceanograficos<BR> Puertos del Estados<BR> Avenida del Partenon -
10<BR> 28042 Madrid<BR> Spain<BR>
  </ADDRESS>

<P> <H2>Region of interest:</H2> <P>

<UL>

<LI>Canary Islands near field at 28&iexcl;N

<LI>Canary Islands far field at 20-35&iexcl;N, 23&iexcl;W (east coast)
</UL>

<P> <H2>Main activity:</H2>

<P> Simulating island processes such as Lee effects, eddy
(formation/structure/dissipation) and upwelling.  The 1'-bathymetry
data file from Ecole des Mines will be used.  <P>

<H2>Interest in obtaining useful elements from collaborations within
the network:</H2> <OL> <LI>Satellite images of SST and ocean colour
showing these island effects and any such other peculiar (interesting)
features of this region.  These data are expected from JRC and ACRI.

<LI>Boundary conditions (flux) as a forcing parameter in the model.
This information is expected from Shirshov Institute of Oceanology.

<LI> In situ measurements from cruises conducted in this region,
providing temperature and chlorophyll concentration as a function of
depth. Such data are expected from Institut f&uuml;r Ostseeforschung and
ACRI.

<LI> Statistical analyses of digitised satellite images and results
from numerical simulations. These analysis should be performed by the
National Institute of Meteorology and Hydrology (Romania).  </OL>

Collaboration is expected through comparison of numerical simulations
with both in situ and satellite data (including detection of features
through a statistical approach).

<P>

<H2>Available to the other partners:</H2>

At Clima Maritimo, CD's with data banks such as Iseler & Hasse
climatological data and NOAA atmospheric data are available.


<ADDRESS> Space Research Institute<BR> Bulgarian Academy of
Science<BR> Moskovska 6, Sofia 1000<BR> Bulgaria
  </ADDRESS> <P>



<H2>Main activities:</H2> <P> <OL> <LI>Physical modelling of
propagation of radiation through atmosphere in the spectral intervals
of satellite data.

<LI>Algorithms and software for deriving atmospheric and sea state
parameters from satellite data.

<LI>Satellite data processing and analyses of particular sea state and
atmospheric phenomena.

<LI>Application of remotely sensed measurements for oceanography, sea
state, atmospheric and climate research.  </OL>

<P>

<H2>Contribution to the Network:</H2>

<P>

<OL> <LI>Models, algorithms and software development (if they are not
available) for deriving sea surface physical parameters (sea surface
temperature, etc) by satellite data (AVHRR, etc).

<LI>Processing and analyses of satellite data in order to estimate and
examine sea state phenomena.

<LI>Models development for atmospheric correction of the remotely
sensed data provided by future satellite systems, considering there
spectral intervals, viewing angles and resolution.

<LI>Modelling and data processing in order to examine the most
informative spectral intervals for estimation of biological, chemical
and physical properties of the sea state, considering the current and
future satellite systems.  </OL>

<ADDRESS> Zentrum f&uuml;r Meeres-und Klimaforschung<BR> Institute
f&uuml;r Meereskunde - Universit&auml;t Hamburg<BR>
Troplowitzstr. 7<BR> D-2000 Hamburg 54<BR> Germany<BR> </ADDRESS>

<H2>Main activity:</H2>

<P> In the frame of the north-eastern Atlantic upwelling system, an
often observed phenomenon (CTD measurement) provides the bases for the
contribution in the project.  In semi-enclosed coastal areas,
anomalous T-S characteristics were observed: from the surface to the
bottom both salinity and temperature show in fact a considerable
increase.  The explanation for such a behaviour is that abrupt, very
intense evaporation events homogenise the water column at the coast,
leading to the formation of a bottom to surface layer, which is
subject to geostrophic adjustment.  It evolves in a bottom arrested
current which mixes with the ambient water and transfers to the bottom
the acquired properties.

<P>

In order to simulate such a phenomenon, a two layer, nonlinear,
hydrostatic shallow water numerical model was developed, which can
describe the evolution of localised layers and the outcropping of a
deep layer.  To achieve this, a set of movable boundary conditions has
been applied, so that the bottom arrested current can find its way on
the ocean floor.  The layers allow for material mixing by means of an
driving parametrization.  The first results show the capability of the
model to reproduce geostrophical ajustment processes.

<P>

<H2>Possible contributions from the other participants:</H2>


The proof of the existence of the quoted phenomenon lies in the
measurements conducted by Institut fuer Ostseeforschung.  In this
context, the availability of the in situ data set is a fundamental
requisite.  It will provide at first a model verification and
validation, and moreover these data could be used by the National
Institute of Meteorology and Hydrology (Romania) to detect significant
statistical time and space variability.  On the other hand, it is
probable that such surface to bottom density anomalies have been
detected by remote sensing means, both in SAR and in surface
temperature, and in colour imagery (in fact, for the last point, the
presence of a bottom arrested current should lead to a decrease in the
phytoplankton content in the water column).  ACRI and Bulgarian Space
Research Institute could carry a inspection of the available remote
sensing imageries to detect the phenomenon.  A quantification of the
forcing playing a role in the phenomenon (wind and heat fluxes) could
represent another aspect of the collaboration with the partners which
are more involved in data acquisition and analysis.

<P>

<H2>Contribution to other network projects:</H2>

We can provide to the other partners the quoted numerical model.  <P>

<ADDRESS> National Institute of Meteorology and Hydrology<BR>
Sos. Bucharesti-Ploiesti 97<BR> 71552<BR> Romania<BR> </ADDRESS>

<P>

<OL> <LI>The original contribution of our team to the network is the
study of the short term climate variability over Atlantic-European
region, due to the air-sea interactions.  The predictive potential of
the North Atlantic Oscillation (NAO) will be assessed by means of
Canonical Correlation Analysis (CCA) and Principal Oscillation Pattern
(POP) applied to sea surface temperature, surface winds and outgoing
longwave radiation (OLR) data.  The effect of air-sea interaction on
European temperature and precipitation anomalies will be also
analysed.

<LI>From the other members of the network, I need some remote sensing
data for the SST and OLR.  From the team of Shirshov Institute of
Oceanology, we hope to get the response of their ocean model to the
surface wind anomalies characteristics for the NAO models.  The
composites of the sea wind characteristic for the NAO phases will be
provided by us.

<LI>For the project proposed by ACRI, we could use the statistical
methods for the validation tasks an for estimating statistically some
parameters of the model.  For projects proposed by Clima Maritimo and
University of Hamburg, we could make statistical analyses of the in
situ and remote sensing observations in order to reveal characteristic
patterns of the phenomena described by their models.  We could also
statistically analyse the output of their models.

</OL>

<P>

<ADDRESS> P. P. Shirshov Institute of Oceanology<BR> 199053
St. Petersburg<BR> Russian Federation<BR> </ADDRESS> <P>

<H2>Work planned to be done:</H2>

<OL>

<LI>Reproducing climatic circulation in the North Atlantic and
seasonal evolution of the upper mixed layer (UML) by means of a
quasi-geostrophic circulation model with interactive upper mixed
layer.

<LI>Development of a robust 4-component
(phytoplankton-zooplankton-detritus-nitrogen) ecosystem model and
coupling it with the circulation model.

<LI>Developing a data assimilation technique directed to fit the
ecosystem model to satellite chlorophyll a concentration data.  </OL>

<P>

<H2>What we will be able to distribute:</H2>

<P>

<OL> <LI>Depths of the UML for the North Atlantic as a function of
time for different geographical regions.  It may be used as an input
for other ecosystem models (for example, that presented by ACRI).

<LI>Volume transport to be used in fine-resolution models for a
concrete region (for example, that studied by Clima Maritimo).

<LI>The data assimilation technique to be developed for utilisation in
other ecosystem models.

</OL>



<H2>What we would like to get from other partners of the network:</H2>


<P> <OL> <LI>Satellite data on chlorophyll a concentration.

<LI>Temporal data on solar radiation measured at some stations (it
would be fine if they are accompanied by temperature and salinity
data).

<LI>Data on surface temperature, cloudiness, wind velocity as well as
fields of temperature, salinity and nutrients in the seasonal and main
thermoclines to be utilised in our circulation model.  </OL>

M&eacute;canique appliqu&eacute;e et Science de l'environnement - ACRI

<ADDRESS> 230, Route du Pin Montard<BR> B. P. 234<BR> 06904 Sophia
Antipolis Cedex<BR> France email: acri@acri.fr http://www.acri.fr
</ADDRESS>


<H2>Activity conducted in the frame of the network subject to
collaborations:</H2>

One of the most important component in models describing the flux of
carbon from atmosphere to ocean sediments is phytoplankton primary
production, i.e. the rate of net carbon fixation. Primary production
represents the input way of inorganic carbon into the ocean organic
carbon pool.  During the last 7 years, efforts have been deployed by
oceanographers, in the frame of the Joint Ocean Global Flux Study
(JGOFS), to develop primary production models applicable at global
scale using remotely sensed variables, namely sea surface chlorophyll
a concentration.  <P> Such a model has been developed by Morel (1991),
and validated and applied at global scale (e.g. Berthon and Morel
1992, Antoine and Morel in press).  Although this model proved to
perform well (measured and prediction values agree within a factor of
3 while primary production varies over 4 orders of magnitude),
improvements are still needed.

<P>

The examination of the different ways allowing significant
improvements of this model led us to identify the depth of the upper
mixed layer (Z<SUB>ml</SUB>) as the most important source of original
information to be added to the model.  Combined with the depth of the
euphotic zone (depth at which irradiance is 1% that at surface;
Z<SUB>e</SUB>), it should provide a better parameterization of depth
variations in chlorophyll a concentration.  Moreover, predictions of
photosynthetic parameters may be for the first time possible.  This
hypothesis can be better <A HREF="select_insitu.html">illustrated
by looking at in situ data recently obtained within the region being
under study by this network</A>.  To test this hypothesis, a huge in
situ data set is being constructed.  It gathers data currently
available within the frame of the Joint Ocean Global Flux Study
(JGOFS).  Up to no, data were gathered from the following JGOFS
programme:



<UL> <LI> ATALANTIS II (US)

<LI>ANTARES (FRANCE)

<LI>BOFS (UK)

<LI>EUMELI (FRANCE)

<LI>OLIPAC/FLUPAC (FRANCE)

<LI>ALMOFRONT (FRANCE)

<LI>DYFAMED (FRANCE)

</UL>


Some of the sites documented by this data set are shown on a
<A HREF="select_map.html">global
map</A>.

<P> To be used in the primary production model of Morel (1991),
Z<SUB>ml</SUB> must be available at a spatial and temporal resolution
similar to that of ocean colour data.  A technique based on remotely
sensed sea surface temperature and wind speed allowing estimation of
Z<SUB>ml</SUB> has recently been proposed by Yan et al. (1991).
Alternatively, Z<SUB>ml</SUB> could be provided by a large-scale
circulation model.  In situ data collected in the area under study
here were also used to feed a model that predicts the
<A HREF="select_fluo.html">rate and efficiency of ocean
surface chlorophyll a sun-induced fluorescence</A>.

<P>

<H2>Possible contribution from the other partners:</H2>

<OL>

<LI> In providing SST and wind speed images (Bulgarian Space Research
Institute).

<LI>In providing a comparison between Z<SUB>ml</SUB> predictions from
Yan's and Shirshov Institute large-scale circulation models.

</OL>

<H2>Contribution to other projects:</H2>

<OL>

<LI>In providing ocean colour images (CZCS) for the Northeast
Atlantic ocean.

<LI>In providing in situ data for validation of small- and large-scale
circulation models.

</OL>
</big>
