</head>
<body background="diox_bg.gif">

<!-- Copyright banner >
<TABLE BORDER=0>
	<TR>
	<TD> <img src="pergamon.gif" ALIGN="ABSMIDDLE"> </TD>
		<TD> <strong> Pergamon </strong> </TD>
		<TD WIDTH=320> </TD>
		<TD WIDTH=300> <font size=-1><i>Energy Convers. Mgmt</i> Vol. 37, Nos 6-8, pp. 1053-1060, 1996<br>
		 Copyright &#169 1996 Elsevier Sciences Ltd</TD>
	</TR>
</TABLE>

<br>
<center>
<h4>
Paper presented to the International Conference<br>
"Greenhouse Gases: Mitigation Options"<br>
 22-25 August 1995, London, UK.<br>
<p></h4>
<h2>
CONCEPTUAL DESIGN OF AN INTEGRATED SOLID CO<font size=-2>2</font> PENETRATOR MARINE DISPOSAL SYSTEM<p>
</h2>
<strong>
*Pierre GUEVEL, **Daniel H. FRUMAN,***<a href="mailto:nicholas.murray@jrc.it">Nicholas MURRAY</a>
</strong>
<p>
* <a href="http://acri.cica.fr">ACRI</a>, B.P. 234, 06904 Sophia Antipolis, France<br>
** ENSTA, Groupe Phnomnes d'Interface, 91120 Palaiseau, France<br>
***  <a href="http://www.jrc.it">Joint Research Centre</a>, 20210 Ispra (VA), Italy<br>
<p>
</center>
<strong>ABSTRACT</strong><p>
<ul><ul>
A disposal technique for carbon dioxide, consisting of burying solid CO<font size=-2>2</font> penetrators into the deep seabed has been proposed. The expected weight of these penetrators can be as large as 1000 tons with lengths between 20 to 40m and  diameters of 4-5m. In order to produce and dispose of such large penetrators, an engineering approach has to be developed to investigate the feasibility of the process from the sources (industrial and thermal electrical production sites) to the sink (deep marine geological formation). A 5 Mt/year  CO<font size=-2>2</font> disposal capacity, has been selected for the study. This corresponds to a 500 MW(e) coal fired power plant assumed to be in the vicinity of a coastal port. The selected penetrators are 540 tons weight, approximately 30m high and 4m diameter. Two concepts have been investigated. The first consists in producing  penetrators at a land based factory and then shipping them to a disposal site in specially designed ships having the capacity of carrying 148 penetrators. The second assumes that liquid CO<font size=-2>2</font>  can be collected from a port facility, transported by a liquid CO<font size=-2>2</font> container ship to a mobile marine penetrator production and launching platform. The cost of these solutions have not been evaluated in the present work.
<p>
</ul></ul><strong><font size=+1>1. INTRODUCTION</font></strong><ul><ul>
<p>
Disposal of CO<font size=-2>2</font> in  deep ocean geological formations potentially appears to be an attractive alternative to a number of disposal concepts recently investigated . Among the options <a href="#ref1">[1]</a> which have been studied are a) transport of gaseous or liquid CO<font size=-2>2</font> by pipeline (GLP) from a land producing plant for ocean disposal at  depth  b) dumping  of non streamlined solid (NSS) CO<font size=-2>2</font> blocks from a ship. In the case of the GLP option, a rapid return of an important fraction of the the injected volumes to the ocean surface will occur because of the density difference between the liquid CO<font size=-2>2</font> and ocean water. The NSS disposal option will be hindered by: i) the fact that a large portion of the solid CO<font size=-2>2</font> will return to the liquid or vapour phase during the slow free-fall of the solid blocks to the sea bottom, ii) the blocks will not penetrate the seabed sediments, and iii) the solid CO<font size=-2>2</font> will dissolve in the deep bottom waters.
<p>
In a possible solution to these problems, <a href="#ref2">[2-3]</a> it has been  proposed to further develop the solid disposal option by streamlining the solid CO<font size=-2>2</font> blocks in order to  shorten the free fall flight time and to reach a much higher terminal velocity before impact with the sea floor [4-5]. As a consequence, depending on their terminal velocity and the mechanical properties of the sediments, the hydrodynamically shaped blocks (called penetrators from here on) will embed themselves within the underlying geological formation. This has been shown using penetrators that were studied as a disposal option for other solid wastes <a href="#ref6">[6]</a>. For the present analysis a depth of 10-15m is considered sufficient to constitute an effective barrier between the solid and the deep ocean water. It has been demonstrated, both theoretically and experimentally <a href="#ref7">[7-8]</a>, that because of the high impact velocities of penetrators, the sediment deformation created by the passage of the device will self-seal and the remoulded sediment column retain similar characteristics to its original properties. This is due to the fact that the low pressure environment acting  in the penetrators wake will cause surface material to collapse behind the incoming vehicle. Thus, an open pathway ( potential by-pass) between the buried penetrator and the deep ocean water is unlikely. Under these circumstances the solid CO<font size=-2>2</font> will physically and chemically  interact with the sediments before reacting with the ocean water. The retention times will, therefore, be significantly increased as compared to the GPL and the NSS solutions.
<p>
It is speculated that the added cost required for producing hydrodynamically shaped penetrators is probably small as compared to the costs of  producing  solid CO<font size=-2>2</font> from the exhaust stack of power generating or other industrial plants, and subsequent fabrication and disposal of NSS blocks. In order to better assess the impact of the streamlined versus the non streamlined solutions, a conceptual engineering design of two alternative disposal options has been undertaken. The first consists in producing the penetrators in a land based factory and shipping them to the disposal site in a specially designed ship  having the capacity of carrying 148 penetrators (~ 80,000 t). The other option assumes a land-based source of liquid CO<font size=-2>2</font>, and subsequent transport of the liquid CO<font size=-2>2</font> by container ship to a mobile production platform containing penetrator fabrication and launching facilities etc.
<p>
</ul></ul><strong><font size=+1>2. CONCEPTUAL DESIGN OF SYSTEM: THE PENETRATORS</font></strong><ul><ul>
<p>
Penetrators will need to be constructed rather rapidly in order to comply with the CO<font size=-2>2</font> disposal requirements of a 500 MW(e) coal fired power plant producing about 540 ton carbon dioxide per hour. Thus on an hourly basis the disposal of such a quantity can be satisfied by a single penetrator or several smaller ones. For a 540 tons penetrator, a tail penetration of >10-15 m can be achieved in soft sediments <a href="#ref3">[3]</a> if the industrially produced CO<font size=-2>2</font> density is of at least 1400 kg/m3, after a free fall of about 1500 m. For the purposes of  discussion such a penetration depth is considered satisfactory for the present disposal scenario. Thus the lower weight limit for a penetrator satisfying a minimum tail emplacement of say ~5m will be about 100t. Solid CO<font size=-2>2</font> penetrators of such a large size can be fabricated either from compacting expanded snow produced from gas or from directly freezing liquid CO<font size=-2>2</font>. The second solution is thermodynamically more efficient [1] and technologically easier and has been selected for the purpose of the present evaluation. Penetrators of 540 t will have an estimated diameter and length of ~ 4m and ~30 m respectively.
<p>
It is assumed that a source of liquid CO<font size=-2>2</font> at atmospheric pressure and a temperature of -78.50C is available at the penetrators production site. Thus in order to fabricate a penetrator a mould is used  consisting of a double wall reinforced metal structure (Fig.1). The unit is designed to withstand  loads developed by both the weight and  thermal stresses of the production process. The outside wall of the mould is isolated in order to diminish heat losses and is reinforced by concentric steel ribs. Incorporated into the inner wall of the mould is a heat exchanger in which cooling fluid circulates. However, since the diameter of the penetrator is so large, the time required to completely transform the liquid into solid by the advancing ice front will be excessively long, thus requiring  too many on-going penetrator production units. In order to accelerate the process, a non recoverable (throw away) aluminium tubular heat exchanger is introduced into the mould at a relatively short distance from the inside wall. The void volume of the mould is then filled with liquid CO<font size=-2>2</font> and cooled by the main and auxiliary heat exchangers.
<p>
<center>
<a href="diox2-figure01.html"><img src="figure08.gif.tn" ALT="Fig1"></a><br>
<a href="diox2-figure01.html">Figure 1. Refrigerated mould for penetrator fabrication (land or platform based production)</a>
</center>
<p>
The function of the auxiliary heat exchanger is not only to accelerate the formation of a thick ice wall but also to serve as a mechanical reinforcement. The auxiliary heat exchanger tubes will be, prior to launch, filled with pressurised liquid CO<font size=-2>2</font> in order to increase their contribution to the structural rigidity of the penetrators. Because production time has to be minimised, only 0,8 m of the outside penetrator diameter will be frozen; the inside core of 2.4 m diameter (representing about 36% of the total volume) will remain in the liquid state. Thus, in order to reach the appropriate density for adequate emplacement, the penetrators have to be ballasted. This is achieved by the addition of an iron nose cone (density 7700 kg/m3) whose weight will be less than 5% of the total penetrator mass. 
<p>
In order to handle the completed penetrators, the solid iron nose cone will be connected by a steel cable to a top plate and clamp. Because the cable is in the liquid CO<font size=-2>2</font> it will be possible to post-stress the penetrator by an appropriate bolt system in order to increase its strength. The tail section (metallic) is made up of fins attached to a thin conic after-structure shaped hydrodynamically to provide flight stability. 
<p>
The mould is fabricated in two halves and can be open by separating them laterally. The  nose cone,  auxiliary spiral internal heat exchanger,  handling cable and conic tail piece and fins are inserted into the open mould. The lower extremity of the collapsed spiral heat exchanger and handling cable are fixed to the nose cone, the top end being attached to an independent winch situated on the top structure of the penetrators fabrication area. 
<p>
Once the mould is closed the internal spiral heat exchanger is drawn to the top of the penetrator by pulling the internal cable and clamped tight. Filling with CO<font size=-2>2</font> will be carried out through ports along the penetrator mould wall. Because of volume shrinkage, as a result of increasing density during freezing, additional liquid CO<font size=-2>2</font> will have to be added through the top of the mould during the freezing process.
<p>
</ul></ul><strong><font size=+1>3. PENETRATOR PRODUCTION PLANT</font></strong><ul><ul>
<p>
The penetrator production plant design will be somewhat different depending whether it is  land based or incorporated in a marine platform. It is assumed in both cases that the coal fired power plant is near the shore and has port facilities either to load  liquid CO<font size=-2>2</font> (in the case of a sea platform) or the finished penetrators (in the case of a land based production plant).The penetrator production plant will, in both cases, consist of a number of dedicated areas: 
<p>
* Power generation plant, liquid CO<font size=-2>2</font> delivery and storage, liquid-to-solid CO<font size=-2>2</font> production unit, fuel delivery and storage,  fabrication area containing  penetrator moulds, penetrator storage (for land based production only), penetrator transfer system to ship (for land based production only), <br>    
* Central control area, communication and logistics (helicopters, ships, etc.), maintenance etc., <br>
* Storage areas for penetrator parts:  nose cones, spiral heat exchangers, cables, tail sections, <br>
* Assembly zone:  nose, heat exchanger, cable and tail section construction. <br>
<p>
</ul></ul><strong><font size=+1>4. DEDICATED PENETRATOR DISPOSAL SHIP</font></strong><ul><ul>
<p>
In the case of the land based production plant, the delivery of the penetrators to the deep disposal sea area is performed by a dedicated ship incorporating the following features: loading, storage and refrigeration facilities, and launch handling system. In order to dispose of carbon dioxide at the same rate as its production from a 500 MW(e) power generating unit (i.e. ~540 tons per hour) a penetrator transport and disposal ship should have a rotation schedule of six days. The total number of penetrators to be transported will be one hundred and forty-eight. The penetrators will be stored in individual reusable refrigerated containers. 
<p>
It is possible to imagine different arrangement for the storage in the ship :
* Horizontally, parallel to the length on three decks ; <br>
* Horizontally, perpendicular to the symmetrical plane of the ship, and also on three decks ; <br>
*Vertically, by introducing reusable refrigerated penetrator containers into individual compartments which themselves contribute to the ship structure.
<p>
Solutions using horizontal arrangement, however, appear to have a number difficulties (mainly technological ones) related to :
i.  Complex handling of very heavy packages during both loading and launching phases, <br>
ii. Recovery and storage of empty containers after launching.
<p>
<center>
<a href="diox2-figure02.html"><img src="figure09.gif.tn" ALT="Fig2"></a><br>
<a href="diox2-figure02.html">Figure 2  Design features of dedicated penetrator disposal ship</a>
</center>
<p>
Thus, concentrating on vertical storage and launching  solutions (which seem to present fewer difficulties), the design of the ship would be as follows (Fig. 2). The central storage area of the ship is partitioned in 148 refrigerated elements (1) of square section (5,5x5,5 meters) and 30 meters high. The ship displacement is estimated to be about 120,000 tons and will be provided with a double hull (4,5 and 6). The penetrators packed in individual insulated refrigerated containers in the production plant, are loaded by crane into each of the compartments in the ship's hold for storage during transport to the disposal site. 
<p>
The disposal of penetrators will be carried out by the means of two moon-pools (2 and 4) served by two cranes (7), respectively moving at the aft and the fore of the ship in order to maintain the initial trim and heel of the vessel during the launching phase. During readiness for launching a penetrators is extracted from its  refrigeration container  by one of the overhead cranes (Fig.2). The penetrator  will be supported and guided by a fixed transverse sliding channel (8) and  a longitudinal frame (9) moving together with the crane, in order to assure stability of the vehicle. The crane will position the penetrator over the moon pool, lower it to is launch depth and release it.
<p>
</ul></ul><strong><font size=+1>5. SEA PLATFORM</font></strong><ul><ul>
<p>
The sea platform architecture (Fig.3) will be structured around a central circular moon pool for the disposal of the penetrators. The central pool is surrounded by an annular production area provided with sliding doors and roofs. There is a rotating gantry crane astride the central pool and annular production area, supported on a circular external track. The crane will : i) pick up the completed penetrators, ii) bring them to the centre of the moon pool, iii) lower them rapidly below the water level and iv) release them. 
<p>
<center>
<a href="diox2-figure03.html"><img src="figure06.gif.tn" ALT="Fig3"></a><br>
<a href="diox2-figure03.html">Figure 3  Plan view of penetrator production and disposal platform</a>
</center>
<p>
The outside wall of the annular production area communicates with a lower annular circulation area necessary to bring the assembled nose cone, spiral heat exchanger and cable, as well as the tail section for each penetrator into the fabrication area. Around the lower circulation area there are  storage zones for the nose cones, spiral heat exchangers, cables and tail sections. Also the assembly and  refrigeration-production areas occupy part of this outer annulus. Satellite structures for energy production, maintenance, control, and housing of personnel will be connected by covered walkways to the central production and launching area. A helicopter pad is incorporated in the platform.
The main platform will be connected to four logistic-service platforms devoted to the docking of  transport ships for liquid CO<font size=-2>2</font>, fuel, penetrator components and personnel. Liquid CO<font size=-2>2</font> and fuel will be stored into the platform buoyancy structures (Fig.4). Those for the liquid CO<font size=-2>2</font> must be pressurised to about 5MPa assuming the water temperature at about 100 m depth is  160C or less. The platform is manoeuvrable using underwater thrusters and employs a Global Positioning System (GPS) for penetrator disposal emplacement. The overall weight of the structure is estimated to be ~ 450,000 tons.
<p>
<center>
<a href="diox2-figure04.html"><img src="figure07.gif.tn" ALT="Fig4"></a><br>
<a href="diox2-figure04.html">Figure 4 Vertical section of platform showing CO<font size=-2>2</font> and fuel storage buoyancy chambers</a>
</center>
<p>
</ul></ul><strong><font size=+1>6. ENERGY REQUIREMENTS</font></strong><ul><ul>
<p>
The power consumption for producing solid CO<font size=-2>2</font> from liquid CO<font size=-2>2</font> is 86 kW/t (which corresponds to 317 kW/t C described in ref. [1])  In order to produce one 540t penetrator per hour, comprising 64% of solid CO<font size=-2>2</font> and 36% of liquid CO<font size=-2>2</font>,  the installed power should be ~ 30 MW. This is the largest single energy requirement for the production system.  In the case of an off-shore platform  power is also needed for the thruster units for the self positioning of the platform and is estimated to be some 10 MW.  Power will also be required for pumping the fluids into the platform reservoirs (200 kW), for pumping the liquid CO<font size=-2>2</font> from the storage buoyancy reservoirs and distributing it throughout the production plant (50 kW). Power  for the auxiliary equipment and living quarters (200 kW) must also be considered although adding only a very limited amount of energy.
<p>
The on-board power plant should be thus designed to provide about 50 MW. Thus energy production for penetrator fabrication will itself be responsible for the emission of about 54 ton CO<font size=-2>2</font> per hour, that is to say approximately two and a half penetrators per day to be disposed as a results of local energy requirements. The effective treatment capacity of the site will be thus reduced to the equivalent of 4.5 Mt CO<font size=-2>2</font>/year.
<p>
</ul></ul><strong><font size=+1>7. CARBON DIOXIDE TRANSPORT</font></strong><ul><ul>
<p>
This preliminary  study has considered for the moment only two options for the transport of carbon dioxide from a coastal site to a disposal area. The first, as liquid carbon dioxide transported in a refrigerated pressurised ship to serve an off-shore penetrator production platform. The second, as solid penetrators individually cooled at atmospheric pressure in a specially designed container-disposal vessel. A further option that has been investigated <a href="#ref9">[9]</a> is that of pumping through pipelines. In this case the CO<font size=-2>2</font> must be compressed to a pressure at which it is either a liquid or a dense phase fluid. Although marine pipelines at 500m depth have been studied <a href="#ref10">[10]</a> the ability to lay them at depths of 1000m or more is still to be demonstrated. However, as deep water technology develops, as it has done over the last two decades, such a option may become operationally and economically viable. 
<p>
For transport over ocean distances shipping remains the only method. One possible long-term alternative to specially designed pressurised low temperature ships could be to consider a dual cycle system combining hydrogen (clean energy) and carbon dioxide. On the basis of a generic formation reaction shown below,  methanol can be formed (Giacomazzi personal communication) and used as hydrogen transport vector. 
<p>
3 H<font size=-2>2</font>  +  CO<font size=-2>2</font>   =  CH<font size=-2>3</font>OH  +  H<font size=-2>2</font>O	
<p>
Exporting methanol from the site of production (large hydro-electric resources for the production of hydrogen), say from Canada, to Europe or Japan, could be carried out in normal bulk-liquid transport ships at atmospheric temperature and pressure.
<p>
On arrival in Europe and Japan the methanol could be pumped from the ship to the penetrator production platform (on the edge of the continental shelf) and catalytically reformed <a href="#ref11">[11]</a> to produce hydrogen and carbon dioxide (using further catalytic oxidation). Once separated hydrogen could be pumped as a gas by pipeline to an on-shore storage facility and the carbon dioxide solidified (the energy being provided by using a fraction of the transported hydrogen) and transformed into penetrators for disposal as described earlier.
Such an option appears interesting as it could perhaps contribute to resolving the problem of inter-continental transport of liquid hydrogen (~ -2530C, 13 atmospheres) as an energy source and at the same time contribute to carbon dioxide elimination. Clearly much more analysis is required to quantify the constraints of such an option.
<p>
</ul></ul><strong><font size=+1>8. CONCLUSIONS</font></strong><ul><ul>
<p>
As compared to the disposal from a ship of non streamlined solid (NSS) CO<font size=-2>2</font> blocks produced at an inland plant, the penetrator option offers major advantages without introducing un-resolvable difficulties for production, handling and disposal and without increasing significantly the power requirements either for land or sea production. Among the advantages of the penetrator option are :
<p>
       i)   losses of CO<font size=-2>2</font>  via thermal dissolution during free fall are sharply reduced, <br>
      ii) large tail embedments (>10m) can be achieved with streamlined bodies produced by moulding, <br>
      iii) very long retention times can be achieved by natural sedimentary geochemical sequestration, <br>
      iv)  core of the penetrators can remain as liquid CO<font size=-2>2</font> (lower energy consumption). <br>
<p>
Production and disposal of the penetrators require :
<p>
       a)  a sophisticated production facility (on land or at sea), <br>
       b) a specialised transport and disposal ship (for the option of  on-land production of penetrators), <br>
       c) a custom designed production and disposal platform, including  important shipping logistics support for CO<font size=-2>2</font> and fuel delivery (for the at-sea penetrator production option). <br>
<p>
Further development of the proposed conceptual designs are necessary to evaluate the fixed and operating costs of the penetrator fabrication plants (on land and at sea) and to optimise the system operation. Alternative CO<font size=-2>2</font> transport methods (pipelines, methanol) should also be considered as they could have implications on overall costs if the technology would be proven to be viable.
<p>
Finally, the complexity and shear size of the operations required to permanently dispose of a significant part of CO<font size=-2>2</font>  emissions from industrial production processes on a planetary scale, for any of the solutions proposed (sea or land production), are clearly considerable. However, the technical difficulties involved do not seem insurmountable compared to the classical problems faced by the offshore gas and petroleum industry. 
<p>
It is nevertheless, clearly necessary to confirm the various assumptions made on the physical, chemical and thermodynamic processes taking  place from the moment of launch of the penetrators to their final emplacement, as well as  their long-term behaviour in  deep marine sedimentary formations. It is thus important to develop theoretical and experimental research (including the investigation of prototype penetrators launched from disused ships) activities to validate (or otherwise) the feasibility of the concept. In this way one would not be caught unprepared if, in the future, the problem of atmospheric pollution by carbon dioxide became critical.
<p>
</ul></ul><strong><font size=+1>ACKNOWLEDGEMENTS</font></strong><ul><ul>
<p>
The authors would like to acknowledge the valuable and lively discussions with Dr. A. Mangin (ACRI, Sophia Antipolis, France) on design considerations of the proposed disposal option. 
<p>
</ul></ul><strong><font size=+1>REFERENCES</font></strong><ul><ul>
<p>
